<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ARTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dueling Leonardos: An Italian artist has claimed in his will that he painted a 
painting previously attributed to Leonardo da Vinci. 
</P>
<P>
The claim was made by Cesare Tubino, who died in Turin, Italy, last week at age 
91, the Turin daily Stampa Sera reported Monday. The "Madonna With Cat" first 
surfaced in the 1930s and was shown at a prestigious Milan exhibition in 1939 
after several experts attributed it to the 15th-Century master. But it 
disappeared soon after and was believed to have been stolen or lost. It was 
found in Tubino's apartment after his death. CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
