<HEADLINE>
<P>
FILENET FACES $500,000 LOSS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COSTA MESA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FileNet Corp., a maker of computerized document processing machines, said 
Monday that it expects to report a loss of $500,000 for its third quarter ended 
Sept. 30, compared to a loss of $1.8 million a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
Revenues are expected to be $22 million, up 18% from $18.6 million a year 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
FileNet said it shipped 19 systems during the quarter, compared to 18 systems a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
The company had announced earlier that it expected its third-quarter earnings 
to be lower than expected, saying customers were delaying orders because of 
concern about the economy and turmoil in the Middle East. The company's 
projections were in line with most current Wall Street estimates. 
</P>
<P>
The company said it expects to release final results for the quarter by Oct. 
22. 
</P>
<P>
FileNet supplies equipment that is used by businesses and government agencies 
to convert paper records into electronic data that computers can understand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
