<HEADLINE>
<P>
ISRAEL SHUTS TEMPLE MOUNT IN BID TO QUELL STRIFE; 
</P>
<P>
MIDEAST: TEAR GAS IS USED ON MUSLIM WORSHIPERS SEEKING TO BREAK THROUGH POLICE 
LINES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Police closed the sacred Temple Mount today and fired tear gas after 200 Muslim 
worshipers tried to break through the cordon. Jerusalem's 80-year-old chief 
Muslim cleric was overcome by tear gas. 
</P>
<P>
The temporary closure came one day after riots on the Temple Mount, Islam's 
third-holiest site, in which at least 19 Palestinians were killed and about 140 
were wounded by police gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
In an Arab neighborhood of Jerusalem today, a Palestinian stabbed two border 
policemen with a screwdriver. The attacker and another Arab were shot and 
wounded, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Clashes between stone throwers and police also erupted in three other Jerusalem 
Arab neighborhoods, and widespread protests were reported in Israeli Arab 
towns, where leaders called for a two-day strike over the Temple Mount 
bloodshed. 
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leaders in the occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip have demanded 
U.N. protection and announced a protest strike beginning today, the start of 
the 36th month of the anti-Israeli uprising in the territories seized during 
the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
<P>
Monday's violence forced the Palestinian question back toward the top of the 
international agenda. It was the bloodiest clash in Jerusalem since the 1967 
war and the highest single-day death toll in the uprising. 
</P>
<P>
Arab leaders denounced the use of deadly force by Israel. President Hosni 
Mubarak of Egypt said the violence could lead to "grave consequences." 
</P>
<P>
Also condemning the Temple Mount violence were Japan, the Soviet Union, the 
European Community's executive body and the president of the European 
Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
Muslim leaders said today's closure of the Temple Mount marked the first time 
police had blocked entry to the 35-acre site and its two mosques since Israel 
captured the surrounding Old City in 1967. The keys to the gates of the wall 
around the Temple Mount were returned to Muslim officials this afternoon, and 
one of the mosque's doors was opened, Muslim clerics said. 
</P>
<P>
Before control of the Temple Mount was returned to the Muslims, the chief 
Muslim cleric, the mufti of Jerusalem, led 200 Muslims to a gate of the shrine. 
Border police blocked their way and ordered them to leave. 
</P>
<P>
When the Muslims refused, police fired tear gas, and the mufti, Saad al-Din 
al-Alami, was overcome, an Arab reporter said. The mufti was taken to Mukassed 
Hospital, where he was reported in satisfactory condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The 80-year-old mufti of Jerusalem, Saad al-Din al-Alami, is carried 
away after being overcome by tear gas at the sacred Temple Mount. Agence 
France-Presse 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
