<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
SOVIETS FINALLY TO SEE 'GWTW' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The movie may not sound romantic as "Unesennye Vetrom." 
</P>
<P>
But in Russian it's "Gone With the Wind," and it's making its premiere in the 
Soviet Union next week. 
</P>
<P>
That's 51 years after the U.S. debut of David O. Selznick's film classic about 
the Civil War that starred Clark Gable and Vivien Leigh. 
</P>
<P>
The film's newest venue will include a fund-raiser in Moscow for fighting AIDS, 
said media tycoon Ted Turner, whose Turner Entertainment Corp. owns the film. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a pleasure to share this crown jewel in the TEC library with the citizens 
of the Soviet Union," Turner said in a statement Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The film's first Soviet screening will be Oct. 19 at Moscow's October Cinema. 
The following night it will be seen in Tbilisi. 
</P>
<P>
The current versions for Soviet consumption are in English with Russian 
subtitles and there are plans to dub a version in Russian for release in 
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
